{
  "local_port": 36914,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why is the Quran written in Arabic?",
  "response": "The Quran is written in Arabic because it was revealed to the Prophet Muhammad in the Arabic language over 1400 years ago in the Arabian Peninsula. Here are several reasons why the Quran remains in Arabic:\n\n1. **Divine Choice**: Muslims believe that the Quran is the literal word of God as revealed to the Prophet Muhammad. The choice of Arabic is considered a divine decision, and the Quran itself emphasizes the beauty and clarity of the Arabic language in several verses.\n\n2. **Originality and Preservation**: The Quran is meant to be preserved in its original form. Translating it into other languages might lead to changes in meaning, as no translation can fully capture the nuances and subtleties of the original Arabic text. Therefore, the Quran is maintained in Arabic to ensure its authenticity and integrity.\n\n3. **Linguistic Miracle**: The Arabic of the Quran is considered a linguistic miracle by Muslims. The Quran's style, eloquence, and rhetorical power are believed to be unparalleled, and translating it would lose these unique qualities.\n\n4. **Religious Practice**: Recitation of the Quran in Arabic is a fundamental part of Islamic worship, including daily prayers and other religious rituals. Muslims around the world learn to recite the Quran in Arabic, even if they do not fully understand the language, as a way to connect with the divine revelation.\n\n5. **Universal Accessibility**: While the Quran is recited in Arabic, translations and interpretations (Tafsir) are available in many languages to help non-Arabic speakers understand its meanings. However, the original text remains in Arabic to maintain its sanctity and universal standard.\n\nIn summary, the Quran is written in Arabic due to its origin, the belief in its divine nature, the importance of preserving its original text, and its role in Islamic religious practice.",
